name: dl-arabinose
Reason: The basic structure of dl-arabinose, a sugar molecule, can be compared to the structure of the simplest sugar, D-ribose, which has a melting point of 87 °C. The dl form of arabinose indicates that there is a mixture of enantiomers, which typically have a lower melting point than the pure enantiomer due to disruption in crystal packing. However, because the actual melting point of dl-arabinose is given as 159 °C, which is higher than that of D-ribose, there must be other factors at play. One possible reason for this increased melting point could be the presence of an aldehyde group instead of an alcohol group at the end of the sugar molecule. Aldehydes can form stronger intermolecular hydrogen bonds with the hydroxyl groups in comparison to an OH group forming hydrogen bonds with another OH group, due to the increased polarity of the C=O bond over the C-O bond. This stronger hydrogen bonding could contribute to a higher packing efficiency in the crystal lattice of arabinose, thus raising its melting point. However, without specific quantitative data on the effect of the aldehyde group versus an alcohol group on the melting point, the influence of this functional group change on the melting point of the sugar can only be estimated.
Prediction: Based on the given actual value of 159 °C for dl-arabinose and assuming that the change to an aldehyde group contributes significantly to this increase, it can be surmised that the aldehyde group increases the melting point significantly, perhaps on the order of +72 °C compared to D-ribose. Thus the prediction based on D-ribose's melting point would be 87 °C (rib) + 72 °C (aldehyde increase) = 159 °C.
